Vice President Kamala Harris delivered a speech on water security at the Indian Treaty Room in the Eisenhower Executive Office Building. She emphasized the growing issue of water scarcity in the United States and around the world, particularly due to climate change and underinvestment in water infrastructure. She highlighted the impact of drought on communities, including wildfires and economic hardships. Harris also discussed the problem of lead pipes and the need for clean and safe drinking water for all Americans. She mentioned the Biden administration's efforts to address these issues, such as investing in water infrastructure and drought resilience. Harris emphasized the global implications of water insecurity, including its impact on food production, public health, and international stability. She discussed the disproportionate burden on women and girls who spend significant time collecting water in many countries. Harris introduced the Action Plan on Global Water Security, which aims to provide access to safe water, share water data and technical expertise, and elevate water security as an international priority. She concluded by emphasizing the interconnectedness of the world and the need for a global solution to water scarcity.